- Eskom gets tariff adjustment that would boost EBITDA materially: Maintain OW- Sibanye-Stillwater reports 1H25 results – Improvement on the back of higher commodity prices and S45X credits – Downgrade 26s to Neutral on valuations- Globalworth 1H25: muted fundamentals but cash intact; Remain Neutral- Turk Telekom renewed its fixed-line concession for \(\) 3bn\(fees- Performance charts - as of Aug 27th, 2025
Prices in this Note are as of the time of writing on Aug \(28^{th}\) 2025

Recall that earlier this year, NERSA awarded Eskom tariff increases of \(12.74\%\) \(5.36\%\) and \(6.19\%\) for the years 2025/6, 2026/27 and 2027/28. The regulator has now acknowledged calculation errors in its MYPD6 tariff decision and agreed to award Eskom additional tariff increases worth R54bn. The tariffs for the next two financial years would be increased to rectify NERSA's error.
Tariff increase for FY26/27 would now be \(8.76\%\) (up from \(5.36\%\)
Tariff increase for FY27/28 would now be \(8.83\%\) (up from \(6.19\%\)

This would be a material positive for Eskom's EBITDA and cash flow, as almost the entire tariff increase should fall to the bottom- line. For FY26/27 (year ending Mar- 27), we now estimate EBITDA of \(\sim\) R105bn, up from our original forecast of R91bn. We expect the company's net leverage to decline to 2.1x by March- 26, and below 2.0x by the following year with cash balance approaching R100bn.

We are OW Eskom curve (ESKOM 28s NG offered at \(z + 256\) ). The NG 28s are still offering a spread pick up of 75bp over SOAF. This has compressed materially over the past year but given Eskom's exceptional financial momentum, we believe this could compress further. In any event, the \(5.9\%\) carry on the bond is quite healthy for a relatively short dated, defensive bond. Zafar Nazim
Sibanye- Stillwater reports 1H25 results – Improvement on the back of higher commodity prices and S45X credits – Downgrade 26s to Neutral on valuations
Our take and recommendation: We downgrade SGLSJ 26 to Neutral on valuations (offered at 98.75, \(z + 138\) , YTW 5.1%) and are Neutral SGLSJ 29s

(offered at 92.5, z+321, YTW 6.6%). As expected, the company's financial performance improved mainly as a result of higher commodity prices, with the positive trend expected to continue in 2H25 and 2026 in light of increasing prices (we calculate 3Q25 to date average gold price at \(\sim\) 33,350/oz, SA PGM basket price at \(\sim\) 1,700/oz and US PGM basket price at \(\sim\) 1,200/oz).

The actual collection of the S45X credits next year would represent a further liquidity boost (in addition to the \(\) 500\mathrm{mn}\$ streaming proceeds received in February). That said, we believe the improving fundamentals are now reflected in bond valuations, hence why we are not compelled to add at these levels across the curve.
Key risks include material changes in PGM and/or gold prices, material operational disruptions or a large cash claim to be paid for the Appian lawsuit.

- (i) Adjusted EBITDA increased to \(\) 818\mathrm{mn}(+130\%)\$ yoy) due to improved earnings across the various segments and also in light of \(\) 285\mathrm{mn}\$ of S45X credits ( \(\) 159\mathrm{mn}\$ for US PGM underground and \(\) 126\mathrm{mn}\$ for US PGM recycling assets).- (ii) Investors may recall that the company previously mentioned that it was eligible to claim a tax credit under Section 45X (S45X) of the US Inflation Reduction Act for minerals produced in the US. In 1H25, Sibanye recognised a \(\) 285\mathrm{mn}\$ credit in cost of sales for S45X (related to the period 2023-1H25), thus boosting profitability for the period. Normalising for this, adjusted EBITDA increased to \(\) 533\mathrm{mn}\$ instead (+50\%\mathrm{yoy}). Management expects the cash inflow from the S45X credits to materialise in 2026.- (iii) Despite operational challenges which resulted in SA gold production decreasing by 13\%\mathrm{yoy}, SA gold EBITDA increased to \(\) 260\mathrm{mn}(+122\%\mathrm{yoy})\$ owing to higher gold price (+38\%\mathrm{yoy}).- (iv) US PGM production dropped by 41\%\mathrm{yoy} \sim 141\mathrm{koz} \mathrm{as} \mathrm{Stillwater} \mathrm{West} \mathrm{mine} \mathrm{was} \mathrm{placed} \mathrm{on} \mathrm{care} \mathrm{and} \mathrm{maintenance} \mathrm{as} \mathrm{previously} \mathrm{planned}.- (v) The construction phase of the Keliber lithium project is on track for completion in 1H26 with management expecting peak capex in 2025 and capex to materially decline from 1H26. That said, the company is assessing various options for this asset on the back of the revision to medium term lithium market fundamentals and price forecasts.- (vi) The company recognised \(\) 526\mathrm{mn}\$ of impairment for the US PGM operations and Keliber lithium project due to an expected decrease in future cash flows (owing to the phase out and termination of S45X credits for the former and lower lithium hydroxide prices for the latter).- (vii) The timeline for the Appian legal proceedings trial is unchanged (the trial is scheduled for November 2025 and judgement expected in 1Q26) with Appian recoverable loss ranging between zero and \(\) 721\mathrm{mn}\$ .

- (i) We calculate FCF of \(\) 187\mathrm{mn}\$ , though we note that this figure also includes the cash proceeds received in February from the streaming arrangement with Franco Nevada ( \(\) 500\mathrm{mn}\$ ). Adjusting for that, we calculate cash burn of \(\) 313\mathrm{mn}\$.-(ii) Mainly on the back of the \(\) 500\mathrm{mn}\$ streaming arrangement, cash increased to \(\sim\) 1.2bn (vs \(\) 855\mathrm{mn}\$ at YE-24). Liquidity amounts to \(\sim\) 2.5bn.- (iii) Net leverage (including leases) decreased to 1.0x (vs 1.9x at YE-24). Adjusting EBITDA for the recognition of \(\) 285\mathrm{mn}\$ S45X credits, we calculate net leverage at 1.4x.- (iv) The company plans to refinance the 26s in 1H26 and during the earnings call
management mentioned it could downsize the notes to $500mn (vs $675mn outstanding).

·(i) In light of the recent PGM price rally (3Q25 SA PGM average basket price is up 16%in ZAR terms vs 1H25), the company expects a material increase in cash flows and earnings for the SA PGM assets in 2H25 should these prices persist.

·(ii) With regards to operating guidance, management commented that all the assets are on track to meet production and cost guidance for 2025, except for SA gold operations.SA gold production guidance was therefore revised down to 480-514koz (vs 514-546koz previously) with AISC guidance increasing to $2,473-2,643/oz (vs $2,319-2,524/oz previously).Lorenzo Parisi

**Globalworth 1H25: muted fundamentals but cash intact; Remain Neutral**

**Our take and recommendation:** Globalworth reported underwhelming operational and financial results with low-single-digit revenue growth, as well as decline in margins and occupancy. That said, the company continued to maintain its cash balance (of €325mn).While management previously expressed preference for acquisitions over bond buybacks,M&A transactions are yet to materialize. Bonds are now callable at 102, but it remains unclear whether the company will tender these in the near-term.
We remain Neutral on the GWILN curve (30s at 102.25, trading to Sep-25 call at 102).

- Noteworthy areas: (a) Net operating income decreased by 7% yoy to €67mn and adj. EBITDA declined by 10% yoy to €57mn at 50% margin. EBITDA decline outpaced revenue due to higher admin costs. Like-for-like (excluding asset sales) NOI and EBITDA increased 2.9% and 1.6%, respectively. (b) The portfolio value increased slightly to €2.6bn, with a \(\sim 1\%\) LFL increase in standing office and mixed-use properties. (c) The average occupancy of the commercial portfolio declined modestly (\(\sim 80\)bps sequentially) to 86%, with Romania's occupancy softening by \(\sim 160\)bps (d) Annualized contracted rent remained stable at \(\sim €188\) mn.

- Cash flow and leverage: LTV remained flat at 38%, below the company's long-term target at 40%. Globalworth ended the period with a cash balance of €325mn. In Apr'25, the €100mn secured facility was refinanced, with maturity extended by five years. Pro forma for this refinancing, the company has €231mn of bank debt coming due before the first bond maturity in 2029, based on FY24 report.

- In 1H25, the company paid an interim cash dividend of €0.5mn with 98% of shareholders opting for scrip dividend. The company also announced an interim cash dividend of \(\sim €15\) mn with no scrip dividend option as bond covenants now permit this payment (if interest coverage ratio is between 2.0x - 2.25x, then up to €50mn dividends could be paid). Nandini Bommakanti/Keshav Maheshwari

The Turkish telecom authority has renewed Turk Telekom's fixed- line concession agreement until 2050, extending it by \(\sim 25\) years. The company will pay a concession fee of \(\) 3bn\(including VAT over the next 10 years. This includes\) \ \(500\mathrm{mn}\) per annum for the next two

years, followed by \(\) 200\mathrm{mn}\$ per annum during 2028- 34 and \(\) 100\mathrm{mn}\$ in 2035 along with a \(\) 500\mathrm{mn}\$ of VAT due this year. The company also pledged to invest \(\) 17\mathrm{bn}\$ in the fixed network and other technologies through 2050.

Turk Telekom aims to fund the VAT payment due this year with cash (eq. to ~\)\\(241\mathrm{mn}\) and undrawn credit facilities (€135mn availability under credit lines). The company could utilize its approval from the Capital Markets Board of Turkiye to issue up to \(\) 1\mathrm{bn}\$ of Eurobonds or sukuks to fund the upcoming concession fee payments. Assuming \(\) 1\mathrm{bn}\$ of additional debt, net leverage could increase by ~0.5x, bringing the pro forma to ~1.2x. This level of net leverage was last observed in FY23. Management alluded to net leverage peaking in FY26e including potential 5G investment, with subsequent deleveraging.

In FY24, the company spent \(\) 0.8\mathrm{bn}\$ on the fixed segment with an average of \(\) 0.7\mathrm{bn}\$ over the last five years. This appears to be the run-rate required to achieve the \(\) 17\mathrm{bn}\$ investment over the next 25 years (capital intensity expected to remain at FY25e guidance level of ~29% in the near-term).

Additionally, Turk Telekom received a wholesale pricing regulation, allowing the company to update tariffs twice a year, by up to the ratio of the most recent domestic PPI to the PPI as of Apr-25. This pricing mechanism is expected to provide long-term visibility.

We are Neutral TURKTI29s (offered at 104.5, z+259bps, 5.9% YTW). While this transaction is leveraging due to significant concession fee payments and the potential 5G auction, the relatively low starting net leverage (0.7x) and potential to expand/upsell fiber packages could drive deleveraging in the medium-term. Nandini Bommakanti

J.P. Morgan uses a bond- level rating system that incorporates valuations (relative value) and our fundamental view on the security. Our fundamental credit view of an issuer is based on the company's underlying credit trends, overall creditworthiness and our opinion on whether the issuer will be able to service its debt obligations when they become due and payable. We analyze, among other things, the company's cash flow capacity and trends and standard credit ratios, such as gross and net leverage, interest coverage and liquidity ratios. We also analyze profitability, capitalization and asset quality, among other variables, when assessing financials. Analysts also rate the issuer, based on the rating of the benchmark or representative security. Unless we specify a different recommendation for the company's individual securities, an issuer recommendation applies to all of the bonds at the same level of the issuer's capital structure. We may also rate certain loans and preferred securities, as applicable. This report also sets out within it the material underlying assumptions used. We use the following ratings for bonds (issues), issuers, loans, and preferred securities: Overweight (over the next three months, the recommended risk position is expected to outperform the relevant index, sector, or benchmark); Neutral (over the next three months, the recommended risk position is expected to perform in line with the relevant index, sector, or benchmark); and Underweight (over the next three months, the recommended risk position is expected to underperform the relevant index, sector, or benchmark). J.P. Morgan Emerging Markets Sovereigns are underweight or issuer because of either a lack of a sufficient fundamental basis or for legal, regulatory or policy reasons. The previous rating no longer should be relied upon. An NR designation is not a recommendation or a rating. NC is Not Covered. An NC designation is not a rating or a recommendation. For CDS, we use the following rating system: Long Risk (over the next three months, the credit return on the recommended position is expected to exceed the relevant index, sector or benchmark); Neutral (over the next three months, the credit return on the recommended position is expected to match the relevant index, sector or benchmark); and Short Risk (over the next three months, the credit return on the recommended position is expected to underperform the relevant index, sector or benchmark).
